<subSubSection pageId="16" pageNumber="61" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="16.[189,310,594,620]" box="[189,310,594,620]" pageId="16" pageNumber="61">
<heading bold="true" box="[189,310,594,620]" fontSize="11" level="3" pageId="16" pageNumber="61" reason="3">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[189,310,594,620]" pageId="16" pageNumber="61">Diagnosis</emphasis>
</heading>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="16.[189,1400,641,773]" pageId="16" pageNumber="61">
The salient features of the new species include: apical right side of the ventral margin of periandrium with a long spinose process, bending upwards, directed cephalad, parallel to periandrium (
<figureCitation box="[1297,1385,676,702]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="17.[189,232,1856,1882]" captionTargetBox="[232,1337,263,1824]" captionTargetId="figure-99@17.[232,1355,255,1827]" captionTargetPageId="17" captionText="Fig. 9. Andes pallidus Wang &amp; Chen sp. nOv., ♂. A. Dorsal view. B. Lateral view. C. Head and thorax, dorsal view. D. Face, ventral view. E. Forewing. F. Genitalia, lateral view. G. Pygofer and gonostyli, ventral view. H. Anal segment, dorsal view. I. Gonostyli, lateral view. J. Aedeagus, right side. K. Aedeagus, left side. L. Aedeagus, dorsal view. M. Aedeagus, ventral view. Scale bars: A–D, F–M = 0.5 mm; E = 1.0 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6862193" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6862193/files/figure.png" pageId="16" pageNumber="61">Fig. 9J</figureCitation>
); apical ventral margin of periandrium with a bifurcated process (
<figureCitation box="[936,1036,711,738]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="17.[189,232,1856,1882]" captionTargetBox="[232,1337,263,1824]" captionTargetId="figure-99@17.[232,1355,255,1827]" captionTargetPageId="17" captionText="Fig. 9. Andes pallidus Wang &amp; Chen sp. nOv., ♂. A. Dorsal view. B. Lateral view. C. Head and thorax, dorsal view. D. Face, ventral view. E. Forewing. F. Genitalia, lateral view. G. Pygofer and gonostyli, ventral view. H. Anal segment, dorsal view. I. Gonostyli, lateral view. J. Aedeagus, right side. K. Aedeagus, left side. L. Aedeagus, dorsal view. M. Aedeagus, ventral view. Scale bars: A–D, F–M = 0.5 mm; E = 1.0 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6862193" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6862193/files/figure.png" pageId="16" pageNumber="61">Fig. 9M</figureCitation>
); endosoma lamellar, basal left side of dorsal margin with small teeth (
<figureCitation box="[648,739,747,773]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="17.[189,232,1856,1882]" captionTargetBox="[232,1337,263,1824]" captionTargetId="figure-99@17.[232,1355,255,1827]" captionTargetPageId="17" captionText="Fig. 9. Andes pallidus Wang &amp; Chen sp. nOv., ♂. A. Dorsal view. B. Lateral view. C. Head and thorax, dorsal view. D. Face, ventral view. E. Forewing. F. Genitalia, lateral view. G. Pygofer and gonostyli, ventral view. H. Anal segment, dorsal view. I. Gonostyli, lateral view. J. Aedeagus, right side. K. Aedeagus, left side. L. Aedeagus, dorsal view. M. Aedeagus, ventral view. Scale bars: A–D, F–M = 0.5 mm; E = 1.0 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6862193" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6862193/files/figure.png" pageId="16" pageNumber="61">Fig. 9L</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="16" pageNumber="61" type="etymology">
<paragraph blockId="16.[189,324,812,838]" box="[189,324,812,838]" pageId="16" pageNumber="61">
<heading bold="true" box="[189,324,812,838]" fontSize="11" level="3" pageId="16" pageNumber="61" reason="3">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[189,324,812,838]" pageId="16" pageNumber="61">Etymology</emphasis>
</heading>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="16.[189,1399,859,920]" pageId="16" pageNumber="61">
The specific name is derived frOm the Latin adjective ‘ 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Wang &amp; Chen" authorityYear="2022" box="[847,942,859,885]" class="Insecta" family="Cixiidae" genus="Andes" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="16" pageNumber="61" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="pallidus">
<emphasis box="[847,942,859,885]" italics="true" pageId="16" pageNumber="61">pallidus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
’, referring to the forewings which are largely pale, white.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
